title: For Sale:  Rare 1981 Ruger Speed Six "9MM"
postcontent: This Speed Six "9MM" is one of two listed on AL now. Incorporating fixed sights and a round-butt frame, and available in .357 Magnum, .38 Special, .38 S&W (.380-200), and 9mm Luger, the Speed-Six was intended for use by plainclothes detectives and others desiring a more concealable handgun. The standard barrel lengths available for these models were the same as those for the Service-Six. The .357 Magnum, three-inch barreled model was standard issue to Special Agents of the former U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service [7] as well as Patrol Agents of the U.S. Border Patrol working plain clothes assignments until both agencies adopted .40 caliber semi-automatic pistols. The .38 S&W and 9MM versions are rare and add upwards of $300 to the BB values to date. Excellent to very fine condition with no rust or freckling or noticeable holster wear. title: For Sale:  Savage Arms Axis 308
location: Boynton Beach, Palm Beach, South Florida
postcontent: Less than 50 rds through. Excellent Condition, no issues. Selling due to financial constraints (new baby, wife says its gotta go)With a similar design to the classic Model 110, but able to stand apart as a unique firearm, the Axis is a dependable, affordable rifle made by the trusted hands at Savage. The crisp Axis trigger has a pull weight of approximately five pounds. The bolt design is the same as the bolt on the trusted Savage 10/110, a design that allows the lugs to bear evenly on both sides in their respective bolt lug recesses at the front of the action, making for very even pressure on the rear of the cartridge case and assuring consistent alignment of the cartridge with the bore. The uniquely designed recoil lug of the Axis action is not sandwiched between the barrel and receiver as in many rifles, but is inserted into the synthetic stock, meaning that when the stock is removed from the barreled action, the recoil lug goes with it. The bolt handle is a unique design as well, having a skeletonized look from the top side, much like the underside of some bolt handles. The detachable box magazine of the Axis is well-crafted, and easy to insert and remove, even while wearing gloves. Among other premium features, the highly accurate Axis includes an attractive, smooth receiver, a heavily textured grip, a free-floated sporter-taper barrel, a very effective recoil pad, and sling swivel studs.

title: For Sale:  J&R Engineering MODEL 80
postcontent: Yes this is not an H&K, but there is no option for this gun and a generic "OTHER" option is also not available.  This is a 9mm carbine, and no option for carbine is provided either.Also - this is a MODEL 80 --- not a model 68 --- very few of the 80's were made before the closed shop have a very rare J&R Engineering  Model 80 9mm carbine.  This came after the model 69 and was the predecessor to the Wilkinson Arms Linda / Terry carbines.  The M80 differs from the M69 by having the charging handle on the side of the receiver instead of the top.  Another distinsion is the adjustable rear sight and rail mount milled into the top of the receiver.  This particular M80 is unique in that it is stamped as a M69.  A mistake when made or they were running out of M80 parts and used what they had before introducing the Linda Carbine.  Yes, there was first a Linda carbine, later changed to the Terry and Linda got the pistol.Used in the TV series Hawaii Five-O with Jack Lord and even in a movie with Sal Minio.  This is also the same gun you will find at Grace Land.   Yes, even the KING owned one of these and is on display there.  I am only the second owner of this carbine as it was purchased from an estate sale in 1993.  I have only fire one mag through it - just to verify it functionedCarbine comes with one 20 rd and four 30 round magazines and a bunch of spare parts ( four recoil springs, two spring guides, firing pin, extractor, ejector and  parts for the lower).  Just clearing out some of my collection
